-- Crude Plummets on Stockpiles; Gold Drops: Commodities at Close
-- B y   C o l i n   M c C l e l l a n d
-- 2012-04-04T22:25:00Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-04-04/crude-plummets-on-stockpiles-gold-drops-commodities-at-close.html
The Standard & Poor’s GSCI  gauge  of
24 commodities declined 2 percent to 683.5 at 3:47 p.m. New York
time. The UBS Bloomberg CMCI  index  of 26 raw materials fell 1.7
percent to 1,592.765.  CRUDE OIL  Oil tumbled after the Energy Department said U.S.
stockpiles surged the most since 2008 as domestic crude output
climbed to the highest level in 12 years.  Crude oil for May delivery dropped $2.54, or 2.4 percent,
to $101.47 a barrel on the New York Mercantile Exchange, the
lowest settlement since Feb. 14. Prices have increased 2.7
percent this year.  Brent oil for May settlement fell $2.52, or 2 percent, to
end the session at $122.34 a barrel on the London-based ICE
Futures Europe exchange. The European benchmark contract settled
at a $20.87  premium  to West Texas Intermediate, the grade traded
in  New York , the widest spread since October.  OIL PRODUCTS  Gasoline fell the most in four weeks after a government
report showed oil inventories rose to the highest level since
June and imports of the fuel increased to a two-month high.  Gasoline for May delivery dropped 6.18 cents to settle at
$3.3336 a gallon on the Nymex. Prices, which touched $3.3049
after the report’s release, have risen 24 percent this year, the
best-performing contract in the Standard & Poor’s GSCI index of
24 commodities.  May-delivery heating oil fell 6.66 cents, or 2.1 percent,
to $3.1609 a gallon on the Nymex. Prices have advanced 7.7
percent this year.  NATURAL GAS  Natural gas futures dropped for the first time in three
days in New York amid speculation that a government report will
show a larger-than-average increase in stockpiles of the heating
and power-plant fuel.  Natural gas for May delivery fell 4.6 cents, or 2.1
percent, to settle at $2.141 per million British thermal units
on the  New York Mercantile Exchange . Gas slid to a 10-year
intraday low of $2.069 per million Btu on April 2.  PRECIOUS METALS  Gold fell to a 12-week low on signs that the  Federal
Reserve  won’t provide more U.S. economic stimulus, boosting the
dollar and eroding the appeal of precious metals as alternative
investments. Silver tumbled 6.7 percent.  Gold futures for June delivery fell 3.5 percent to settle
at $1,614.10 an ounce at 1:35 p.m. on the Comex in New York, the
biggest drop for a most-active contract since Feb. 29.  Silver posted the biggest decline among 24  raw materials  in
the Standard & Poor’s GSCI Spot Index, falling to $31.044 an
ounce. Nickel, copper and lead also slumped.  Palladium futures for June delivery fell 4.1 percent to
$632.75 an ounce on the Nymex.  BASE METALS  Copper fell by the most since December after the Fed damped
expectations for additional economic stimulus.  Copper futures for May delivery slid 3.3 percent to settle
at $3.7905 a pound at 1:20 p.m. on the Comex in New York, the
biggest drop since Dec. 14.  On the  London  Metal Exchange, copper for delivery in three
months tumbled 3.1 percent to $8,350 a metric ton ($3.79 a
pound).  Zinc, lead, aluminum, nickel and tin also slumped in
London.  GRAINS, SOFT COMMODITIES  Soybeans gained for the second time in three sessions after
government forecasts last week signaled tighter supplies in the
U.S., the world’s top producer. Corn fell.  Soybean futures for May delivery gained 0.2 percent, to
close at $14.195 a bushel at 1:15 p.m. on the Chicago Board of
Trade. The oilseed has gained 18 percent this year after hot,
dry weather cut yields in  Brazil , the second-biggest producer,
and  Argentina , the third-largest.  Corn futures for May delivery fell 0.2 percent to $6.5675 a
bushel on the CBOT. The price jumped 9 percent in the previous
three sessions.  Wheat futures for May delivery dropped 2.8 percent to
$6.3925 a bushel.  Cocoa fell to the lowest level since January on signs of
improved crop prospects in  Ivory Coast , the world’s top
producer. Coffee dropped, and sugar gained.  Cocoa futures for May delivery dropped 2.8 percent to
settle at $2,083 a metric ton at 12:05 p.m. on ICE Futures U.S.
in New York. Prices have fallen for six straight sessions, the
longest slide since Dec. 9.  Arabica-coffee futures for May delivery fell 0.3 percent to
$1.8475 a pound in New York.  Raw-sugar futures for July delivery climbed 0.3 percent to
23.54 cents a pound on ICE.  In London futures trading, cocoa and robusta coffee slid on
NYSE Liffe. Refined sugar rose.  LIVESTOCK  Cattle futures slumped to a six-month low on signs of
slowing demand for U.S. beef. Hogs rose.  Cattle futures for June delivery declined 0.8 percent to
settle at $1.15125 a pound at 1 p.m. on the  Chicago  Mercantile
Exchange.  Feeder-cattle futures for May settlement fell less than 0.1
percent to $1.482 a pound in Chicago.  Hog futures for June settlement advanced 0.4 percent to 92
cents a pound.  To contact the reporter on this story:
